1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,580
 - Good morning, UV.

2
00:00:01,580 --> 00:00:05,500
 (speaking in foreign language)

3
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:06,840
 Testing, testing.

4
00:00:06,840 --> 00:00:07,660
 Okay.

5
00:00:07,660 --> 00:00:08,500
 All right.

6
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:10,840
 So when you think about God,

7
00:00:10,840 --> 00:00:13,840
 what are some of the image or words

8
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:15,840
 that comes to your mind?

9
00:00:15,840 --> 00:00:21,840
 Is he a wrathful God, or is he a loving father?

10
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:26,880
 Is he a mighty warrior, or a humble servant?

11
00:00:28,140 --> 00:00:31,320
 Is he someone that is quick to punish,

12
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:34,600
 like a parking attendant that is always out there

13
00:00:34,600 --> 00:00:36,980
 roaming the streets and will not hesitate

14
00:00:36,980 --> 00:00:38,980
 to give out a parking ticket,

15
00:00:38,980 --> 00:00:42,440
 even though your meter only expires for a few seconds?

16
00:00:42,440 --> 00:00:45,440
 Or is he slow to anger, like a teacher

17
00:00:45,440 --> 00:00:47,900
 that is always patient with his students

18
00:00:47,900 --> 00:00:52,060
 despite all the repeated mistakes and questions from them?

19
00:00:52,060 --> 00:00:57,400
 (speaking in foreign language)

20
00:00:58,320 --> 00:01:02,240
 (speaking in foreign language)

21
00:01:02,240 --> 00:01:06,160
 (speaking in foreign language)

22
00:01:06,160 --> 00:01:10,080
 (speaking in foreign language)

23
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:33,500
 A.W. Tozer famously said, "What comes into our mind

24
00:01:33,500 --> 00:01:36,920
 "when we think about God is the most important things

25
00:01:36,920 --> 00:01:38,260
 "about us."

26
00:01:38,260 --> 00:01:41,180
 And so what he means here is that the way we view God

27
00:01:41,180 --> 00:01:43,420
 actually shapes the way we live.

28
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:45,260
 So let me give you a quick example.

29
00:01:45,260 --> 00:01:47,380
 If we think of God as a vengeful God

30
00:01:47,380 --> 00:01:49,720
 that is always out there to get us,

31
00:01:49,720 --> 00:01:51,680
 we will probably live in constant fear

32
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:54,640
 of doing something wrong or mess up, right?

33
00:01:54,640 --> 00:01:58,400
 But on the flip side, if we see God as a loving father,

34
00:01:58,400 --> 00:02:00,720
 when we mess up, he will be the first person

35
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:04,980
 that we run towards and ask for forgiveness, right?

36
00:02:04,980 --> 00:02:09,900
 (speaking in foreign language)

37
00:02:09,900 --> 00:02:13,820
 (speaking in foreign language)

38
00:02:13,820 --> 00:02:17,740
 (speaking in foreign language)

39
00:02:17,740 --> 00:02:21,660
 (speaking in foreign language)

40
00:02:46,460 --> 00:02:49,300
 So this morning we will continue our sermon series

41
00:02:49,300 --> 00:02:51,000
 in the Book of Judges.

42
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:53,960
 And so far we have looked at the double introduction

43
00:02:53,960 --> 00:02:57,300
 sections that sets us up on the historical narrative

44
00:02:57,300 --> 00:02:59,580
 of Israel up to this point.

45
00:02:59,580 --> 00:03:02,880
 That Israel, they was in the promised land already,

46
00:03:02,880 --> 00:03:05,840
 but they failed to completely drive out the inhabitants

47
00:03:05,840 --> 00:03:09,840
 in the land of Canaan as the Lord has commanded them.

48
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:11,460
 And we see that as a result of that,

49
00:03:11,460 --> 00:03:14,140
 the idol worship culture of the Canaanites,

50
00:03:14,140 --> 00:03:16,460
 they slowly seep into Israel.

51
00:03:16,460 --> 00:03:18,340
 And these people of Israelites,

52
00:03:18,340 --> 00:03:21,500
 they turn to worship these false Canaanites gods

53
00:03:21,500 --> 00:03:23,980
 instead of worshiping Yahweh himself.

54
00:03:23,980 --> 00:03:28,980
 (speaking in foreign language)

55
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:32,900
 (speaking in foreign language)

56
00:03:32,900 --> 00:03:56,500
 Moreover, the introduction section also gives us

57
00:03:56,500 --> 00:04:00,740
 a framework on Israel's spiritual and moral downfall

58
00:04:00,740 --> 00:04:03,420
 that we will see repeating itself in the cyclical patterns

59
00:04:03,420 --> 00:04:06,860
 towards rock bottom for Israel both as a nation

60
00:04:06,860 --> 00:04:08,940
 and as God's chosen people.

61
00:04:08,940 --> 00:04:14,060
 (speaking in foreign language)

62
00:04:14,380 --> 00:04:18,300
 (speaking in foreign language)

63
00:04:18,300 --> 00:04:29,500
 However, while Judges highlights God's people

64
00:04:29,500 --> 00:04:31,900
 at its worst, more importantly,

65
00:04:31,900 --> 00:04:36,340
 I think it also show us God's response to human's actions.

66
00:04:36,340 --> 00:04:38,660
 And through God's response to Israel's rebellion

67
00:04:38,660 --> 00:04:43,340
 and disobedience, we get a clearer picture of who he is

68
00:04:43,340 --> 00:04:45,100
 and what he is like.

69
00:04:45,100 --> 00:04:47,140
 And so today we will go into the main section

70
00:04:47,140 --> 00:04:48,900
 of the book of Judges and look at the story

71
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:51,420
 of a judge called Ehud.

72
00:04:51,420 --> 00:04:53,460
 Ehud is probably a lesser known judge,

73
00:04:53,460 --> 00:04:55,060
 but through this narrative,

74
00:04:55,060 --> 00:04:56,980
 we will explore this particular character

75
00:04:56,980 --> 00:05:00,460
 about God together, that is his holy love.

76
00:05:00,460 --> 00:05:04,380
 (speaking in foreign language)

77
00:05:05,380 --> 00:05:09,300
 (speaking in foreign language)

78
00:05:09,300 --> 00:05:13,220
 (speaking in foreign language)

79
00:05:13,220 --> 00:05:35,300
 But before we dive into it,

80
00:05:35,300 --> 00:05:37,140
 just a few notes on this main section

81
00:05:37,140 --> 00:05:38,700
 of the book of Judges.

82
00:05:38,700 --> 00:05:41,740
 The main section of Judges has six major judge stories

83
00:05:41,740 --> 00:05:43,220
 based upon this cycle.

84
00:05:43,220 --> 00:05:48,260
 (speaking in foreign language)

85
00:05:48,260 --> 00:06:00,940
 So a quick review of the components of these cycles.

86
00:06:00,940 --> 00:06:03,940
 It usually begins like this.

87
00:06:03,940 --> 00:06:06,780
 Israel does evil in the eyes of the Lord

88
00:06:06,780 --> 00:06:08,780
 and the Lord will gives or sells them

89
00:06:08,780 --> 00:06:10,940
 into the hands of their oppressors.

90
00:06:10,940 --> 00:06:12,740
 And Israel will serve their oppressors

91
00:06:12,740 --> 00:06:14,900
 for a certain amount of years.

92
00:06:14,900 --> 00:06:17,300
 And after that, Israel will cry out to the Lord

93
00:06:17,300 --> 00:06:21,140
 and the Lord will raise up for them a deliverer or a judge.

94
00:06:21,140 --> 00:06:22,780
 And the oppressor is subdued

95
00:06:22,780 --> 00:06:26,620
 and the land has rest and peace for a certain amount of years

96
00:06:26,620 --> 00:06:29,260
 before the cycle repeats itself again.

97
00:06:29,260 --> 00:06:33,180
 (speaking in foreign language)

98
00:06:33,780 --> 00:06:37,700
 (speaking in foreign language)

99
00:06:37,700 --> 00:06:56,540
 And as we dive into this narrative cycle of the major judge,

100
00:06:56,540 --> 00:06:58,180
 I want us to keep in mind that

101
00:06:58,180 --> 00:07:00,580
 these individual narratives of the judge

102
00:07:00,580 --> 00:07:04,620
 of Othniel, of Ehud, of Deborah, of Gideon,

103
00:07:04,620 --> 00:07:06,380
 Jethta and Samson,

104
00:07:06,380 --> 00:07:09,540
 they should not be read in isolation from one another.

105
00:07:09,540 --> 00:07:11,340
 But together they actually make up a long

106
00:07:11,340 --> 00:07:13,260
 and complex narrative movement

107
00:07:13,260 --> 00:07:15,060
 that shows Israel's slow descents

108
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:18,500
 into religious apostasy and moral downfall.

109
00:07:18,500 --> 00:07:20,020
 One that is being introduced already

110
00:07:20,020 --> 00:07:21,780
 in the double introduction section.

111
00:07:21,780 --> 00:07:26,620
 (speaking in foreign language)

112
00:07:27,300 --> 00:07:31,220
 (speaking in foreign language)

113
00:07:31,220 --> 00:07:55,540
 So the first few major judge will be mostly positive,

114
00:07:55,540 --> 00:07:58,020
 including our judge for today, Ehud.

115
00:07:58,020 --> 00:08:00,300
 But the further we actually go into the book,

116
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:02,980
 the more issues we find with these judges.

117
00:08:02,980 --> 00:08:04,540
 And this is actually being reflected

118
00:08:04,540 --> 00:08:07,220
 in the writings of judges as well.

119
00:08:07,220 --> 00:08:09,700
 The further we go into the main cycle section,

120
00:08:09,700 --> 00:08:12,020
 the less consistent each of these components

121
00:08:12,020 --> 00:08:14,300
 appears on the narrative.

122
00:08:14,300 --> 00:08:17,220
 And when we come to the last judge of Samson,

123
00:08:17,220 --> 00:08:19,540
 only the first three components were left.

124
00:08:19,540 --> 00:08:22,100
 And they didn't even cry out to the Lord at that point,

125
00:08:22,100 --> 00:08:23,580
 which again shows the chaos

126
00:08:23,580 --> 00:08:25,460
 that Israel has descended into.

127
00:08:25,460 --> 00:08:30,420
 (speaking in foreign language)

128
00:08:30,420 --> 00:08:34,340
 (speaking in foreign language)

129
00:08:34,340 --> 00:08:57,060
 Okay, so with that said,

130
00:08:57,060 --> 00:08:59,620
 let's dive into our passage on Ehud

131
00:08:59,620 --> 00:09:02,980
 from Judges 3 today and look at what it means

132
00:09:02,980 --> 00:09:05,380
 for God to be a God of holy love.

133
00:09:05,380 --> 00:09:08,100
 And more specifically, we will look at God's holy love

134
00:09:08,100 --> 00:09:11,060
 from the way he responds to our human action.

135
00:09:11,060 --> 00:09:13,180
 So let's look at verse 12 together.

136
00:09:13,180 --> 00:09:16,940
 It says, "Again, the Israelites did evils

137
00:09:16,940 --> 00:09:18,620
 "in the eyes of the Lord.

138
00:09:18,620 --> 00:09:20,280
 "And because they did this evil,

139
00:09:20,280 --> 00:09:24,320
 "the Lord gave Aglon, king of Moab, power over Israel.

140
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:26,940
 "Getting the Ammonites and Amalekites to join him,

141
00:09:26,940 --> 00:09:29,140
 "Aglon came and attacked Israel,

142
00:09:29,140 --> 00:09:32,200
 "and they took possessions of the city of Palms.

143
00:09:32,200 --> 00:09:34,580
 "The Israelites, they were subject to Aglon,

144
00:09:34,580 --> 00:09:37,540
 "king of Moab, for 18 years."

145
00:09:37,540 --> 00:09:41,460
 (speaking in foreign language)

146
00:09:41,460 --> 00:09:45,380
 (speaking in foreign language)

147
00:09:45,380 --> 00:10:13,700
, okay.

148
00:10:13,700 --> 00:10:18,700
 So we will first focus on God's holiness this morning,

149
00:10:18,700 --> 00:10:21,500
 especially in the way he disciplines

150
00:10:21,500 --> 00:10:24,180
 and punish his own people.

151
00:10:24,180 --> 00:10:28,180
 (speaking in foreign language)

152
00:10:28,180 --> 00:10:34,980
 So if you notice, verse 12 begins with the word again.

153
00:10:34,980 --> 00:10:36,160
 Why again?

154
00:10:36,160 --> 00:10:39,060
 Because this is not the first time Israel has done evil

155
00:10:39,060 --> 00:10:40,860
 in the eyes of the Lord.

156
00:10:40,860 --> 00:10:43,500
 Earlier in the chapter, in the first judges story

157
00:10:43,500 --> 00:10:46,820
 in verse seven, we read that the Israelites did evils

158
00:10:46,820 --> 00:10:48,340
 in the eyes of the Lord.

159
00:10:48,340 --> 00:10:50,100
 They forgot the Lord their God

160
00:10:50,100 --> 00:10:52,860
 and served the Baals and the Asherahs.

161
00:10:52,860 --> 00:10:55,860
 So the again here highlights that this is actually

162
00:10:55,860 --> 00:10:58,660
 a repeated offense from Israel.

163
00:10:58,660 --> 00:11:02,580
 (speaking in foreign language)

164
00:11:02,580 --> 00:11:25,260
 And how did God respond to it?

165
00:11:25,260 --> 00:11:28,460
 We see that the Lord gave Aglon, king of Moab,

166
00:11:28,460 --> 00:11:30,380
 power over Israel.

167
00:11:30,380 --> 00:11:32,180
 Aglon came and attacked Israel

168
00:11:32,180 --> 00:11:34,980
 and they took possessions of the city of Palms.

169
00:11:34,980 --> 00:11:38,260
 And the Israelites, they were subject to king of Moab

170
00:11:38,260 --> 00:11:39,820
 for 18 years.

171
00:11:39,820 --> 00:11:44,980
 (speaking in foreign language)

172
00:11:44,980 --> 00:12:08,980
 A lot of times when we read a passage of God

173
00:12:08,980 --> 00:12:11,060
 punishing his people like this,

174
00:12:11,060 --> 00:12:14,340
 we can be tempted to think of God as a wrathful

175
00:12:14,340 --> 00:12:15,980
 and vengeful God.

176
00:12:15,980 --> 00:12:19,060
 And if we make a mistake, he will be out there to punish us

177
00:12:19,060 --> 00:12:21,260
 like the parking attendant that is always out there

178
00:12:21,260 --> 00:12:23,060
 to ticket people.

179
00:12:23,060 --> 00:12:26,980
 (speaking in foreign language)

180
00:12:26,980 --> 00:12:41,140
 This even leads some people to conclude

181
00:12:41,140 --> 00:12:43,500
 that the God of the Old Testament,

182
00:12:43,500 --> 00:12:46,060
 who is often portrayed as a God of wrath,

183
00:12:46,060 --> 00:12:48,900
 cannot be the same as the God of the New Testament,

184
00:12:48,900 --> 00:12:51,860
 who is usually portrayed as a God of love.

185
00:12:51,860 --> 00:12:55,860
 (speaking in foreign language)

186
00:12:55,860 --> 00:13:03,340
 For example, in the second century,

187
00:13:03,340 --> 00:13:06,300
 an early Christian theologian named Martian of Sinai,

188
00:13:06,300 --> 00:13:09,340
 he taught that the creator God of the Old Testament

189
00:13:09,340 --> 00:13:11,780
 was a different and inferior God,

190
00:13:11,780 --> 00:13:15,820
 harsh, legalistic, and judgmental.

191
00:13:15,820 --> 00:13:18,860
 In contrast, he taught that the God revealed by Jesus

192
00:13:18,860 --> 00:13:22,820
 in the New Testament was a higher and more supreme God,

193
00:13:22,820 --> 00:13:26,780
 purely loving, gracious, and merciful.

194
00:13:26,780 --> 00:13:28,820
 And this eventually led him to actually reject

195
00:13:28,820 --> 00:13:31,580
 the Old Testament as it only revealed

196
00:13:31,580 --> 00:13:34,340
 a lesser and inferior God.

197
00:13:34,340 --> 00:13:38,260
 (speaking in foreign language)

198
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:42,980
 And so for people like Martians and any modern manifestation

199
00:13:42,980 --> 00:13:46,620
 of this kind of thinking, it's not surprising that,

200
00:13:46,620 --> 00:13:48,260
 in the early Christian tradition,

201
00:13:48,260 --> 00:13:50,900
 the Old Testament was a God of love.

202
00:13:50,900 --> 00:13:54,820
 (speaking in foreign language)

203
00:13:55,820 --> 00:13:59,140
 And so for people like Martians and any modern manifestation

204
00:13:59,140 --> 00:14:01,900
 of this kind of thinking and belief about God,

205
00:14:01,900 --> 00:14:04,500
 there is a clear misunderstanding about who God is

206
00:14:04,500 --> 00:14:06,660
 and what He is like.

207
00:14:06,660 --> 00:14:08,340
 Yes, God is love.

208
00:14:08,340 --> 00:14:09,980
 Yes, God is holy.

209
00:14:09,980 --> 00:14:12,780
 But God is not wrath.

210
00:14:12,780 --> 00:14:15,260
 Wrath is not an essential attribute of God,

211
00:14:15,260 --> 00:14:18,420
 but wrath is a rightful attribute of God.

212
00:14:18,420 --> 00:14:22,340
 (speaking in foreign language)

213
00:14:22,340 --> 00:14:23,500
 Not an essential attribute of God,

214
00:14:23,500 --> 00:14:27,700
 but wrath is a rightful expression of God's holiness

215
00:14:27,700 --> 00:14:29,380
 in response to evil.

216
00:14:29,380 --> 00:14:34,060
 To put it another way, wrath is not part of God's character,

217
00:14:34,060 --> 00:14:35,980
 but when God sees evils,

218
00:14:35,980 --> 00:14:40,100
 His holiness compels Him to respond in righteous anger

219
00:14:40,100 --> 00:14:42,380
 because God hates evil.

220
00:14:42,380 --> 00:14:46,300
 (speaking in foreign language)

221
00:14:46,300 --> 00:14:48,540
 And so this is what we can learn about God

222
00:14:48,540 --> 00:14:51,300
 in His response towards human beings.

223
00:14:51,300 --> 00:14:55,220
 (speaking in foreign language)

224
00:14:55,220 --> 00:15:14,820
 And so this is what we can learn about God

225
00:15:14,820 --> 00:15:18,300
 in His response towards human weakness here.

226
00:15:18,300 --> 00:15:23,100
 In essence, God is a holy God and He cannot tolerate evil,

227
00:15:23,100 --> 00:15:25,820
 not even just a little bit of it.

228
00:15:25,820 --> 00:15:29,740
 (speaking in foreign language)

229
00:15:29,740 --> 00:15:38,700
 More importantly, God's holiness usually goes hand in hand

230
00:15:38,700 --> 00:15:40,820
 with His love as well.

231
00:15:40,820 --> 00:15:43,300
 Just as a loving parent who would not spare the rod

232
00:15:43,300 --> 00:15:45,780
 of discipline towards their children,

233
00:15:45,780 --> 00:15:48,900
 God's discipline or punishment towards His children

234
00:15:48,900 --> 00:15:50,980
 always comes from a place of love

235
00:15:50,980 --> 00:15:53,500
 in order to bring them back to Himself as well.

236
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:59,660
 (speaking in foreign language)

237
00:15:59,660 --> 00:16:12,700
 And when it comes to God's punishment,

238
00:16:12,700 --> 00:16:16,460
 there's always a limit and a greater purpose behind it

239
00:16:16,460 --> 00:16:18,260
 because God doesn't just punish people

240
00:16:18,260 --> 00:16:20,780
 for the sake of punishment alone.

241
00:16:20,780 --> 00:16:23,740
 You can think of God's punishment as more like a timeout

242
00:16:23,740 --> 00:16:26,460
 that a parent would give to a children.

243
00:16:26,460 --> 00:16:29,380
 This is because ultimately, His judgment,

244
00:16:29,380 --> 00:16:32,300
 His punishment, and His disciplines,

245
00:16:32,300 --> 00:16:35,740
 they all comes from His character as a holy God,

246
00:16:35,740 --> 00:16:39,060
 as a loving father, and the perfect judge.

247
00:16:39,060 --> 00:16:40,340
 And so when God acts,

248
00:16:40,340 --> 00:16:43,580
 all of these characters act in perfect unison.

249
00:16:43,580 --> 00:16:49,100
 (speaking in foreign language)

250
00:16:49,100 --> 00:17:07,940
 And so this is what we see in our passage here.

251
00:17:07,940 --> 00:17:10,660
 For 18 years, Israel was powerless

252
00:17:10,660 --> 00:17:12,660
 against Aglon, king of Moab,

253
00:17:12,660 --> 00:17:15,700
 because the Lord gave Aglon power over Israel

254
00:17:15,700 --> 00:17:18,940
 as a way of disciplining his own people.

255
00:17:18,940 --> 00:17:21,140
 And finally, after 18 years of oppressions

256
00:17:21,140 --> 00:17:22,860
 under the hands of Moab,

257
00:17:22,860 --> 00:17:26,340
 Israel finally shows some signs of repentance.

258
00:17:26,340 --> 00:17:28,300
 And we'll see how God responds.

259
00:17:28,300 --> 00:17:30,580
 So let's look at verse 15 together.

260
00:17:30,580 --> 00:17:35,060
 Again, the Israelites cried out to the Lord,

261
00:17:35,060 --> 00:17:38,300
 and He gave them a deliverer, Ehud,

262
00:17:38,300 --> 00:17:41,940
 a left-handed man, the son of Gerar the Benjamite.

263
00:17:41,940 --> 00:17:43,620
 The Israelites sent him with tribute

264
00:17:43,620 --> 00:17:45,780
 to Aglon, king of Moab.

265
00:17:45,780 --> 00:17:49,700
 (speaking in foreign language)

266
00:17:49,700 --> 00:17:53,620
 (speaking in foreign language)

267
00:17:53,620 --> 00:17:57,540
 (speaking in foreign language)

268
00:17:57,540 --> 00:18:23,540
 And this brings me to the second focus for today.

269
00:18:23,540 --> 00:18:26,580
 That is God's love in His deliverance.

270
00:18:26,580 --> 00:18:31,140
 (speaking in foreign language)

271
00:18:31,140 --> 00:18:33,180
 So while God's holiness compels Him

272
00:18:33,180 --> 00:18:37,140
 to respond to the wickedness of His people with wrath,

273
00:18:37,140 --> 00:18:38,540
 His love, on the other hand,

274
00:18:38,540 --> 00:18:41,180
 compels Him to respond to the crying out

275
00:18:41,180 --> 00:18:43,140
 with mercy as well.

276
00:18:43,140 --> 00:18:45,220
 And so when the Israelites cried out to the Lord

277
00:18:45,220 --> 00:18:47,540
 after 18 years of oppressions

278
00:18:47,540 --> 00:18:49,780
 under king Aglon of Moab,

279
00:18:49,780 --> 00:18:52,300
 He gave them a deliverer, Ehud.

280
00:18:53,380 --> 00:18:57,300
 (speaking in foreign language)

281
00:18:57,300 --> 00:19:15,900
 And we didn't look at the story of the first judge,

282
00:19:15,900 --> 00:19:18,060
 but compared to the first judge, Othniel,

283
00:19:18,060 --> 00:19:20,820
 who is a leader and a warrior,

284
00:19:20,820 --> 00:19:23,980
 Ehud, he's a very different kind of judge.

285
00:19:23,980 --> 00:19:26,500
 We learned that he is a left-handed man,

286
00:19:26,500 --> 00:19:29,420
 or more literally, he is a man restricted

287
00:19:29,420 --> 00:19:31,700
 in his right hand, which is the dominant hand

288
00:19:31,700 --> 00:19:33,060
 in that culture.

289
00:19:33,060 --> 00:19:35,100
 And so this gives him the appearance

290
00:19:35,100 --> 00:19:37,860
 of weakness in some sense.

291
00:19:37,860 --> 00:19:41,780
 (speaking in foreign language)

292
00:19:41,780 --> 00:19:46,780
, moreover, Ehud is also not a leader in Israel,

293
00:19:46,780 --> 00:20:04,700
 but he's just someone being tasked with the job

294
00:20:04,700 --> 00:20:08,500
 of bringing tribute to Aglon king of Moab.

295
00:20:08,500 --> 00:20:12,420
 (speaking in foreign language)

296
00:20:12,420 --> 00:20:17,580
 And yet through a series of trickery and satire,

297
00:20:17,580 --> 00:20:19,940
 we will see that the Lord will actually use

298
00:20:19,940 --> 00:20:22,660
 this seemingly unassuming person, Ehud,

299
00:20:22,660 --> 00:20:26,420
 to deliver Israel from the hand of Aglon, king of Moab.

300
00:20:26,420 --> 00:20:31,180
 (speaking in foreign language)

301
00:20:31,180 --> 00:20:35,100
 (speaking in foreign language)

302
00:20:35,100 --> 00:20:41,140
 So let's go through the rest of our story.

303
00:20:41,140 --> 00:20:44,860
 Verse 16, "Now Ehud had made a double-edged sword

304
00:20:44,860 --> 00:20:47,060
 "about a cubit long, which he strapped

305
00:20:47,060 --> 00:20:49,860
 "to his right thigh under his clothing.

306
00:20:49,860 --> 00:20:52,980
 "He presented the tribute to Aglon, king of Moab,

307
00:20:52,980 --> 00:20:55,180
 "who was a very fat man.

308
00:20:55,180 --> 00:20:57,260
 "And after Ehud had presented the tribute,

309
00:20:57,260 --> 00:21:00,380
 "he sent on their way those who had carried it.

310
00:21:00,380 --> 00:21:02,980
 "But on reaching the stone images near Gilgal,

311
00:21:02,980 --> 00:21:06,140
 "he himself went back to Aglon and said,

312
00:21:06,140 --> 00:21:09,900
 "Your Majesty, I have a secret message for you.

313
00:21:09,900 --> 00:21:12,020
 "And the king said to his attendants,

314
00:21:12,020 --> 00:21:14,180
 "Leave us, and they all left."

315
00:21:14,180 --> 00:21:19,060
 (speaking in foreign language)

316
00:21:19,060 --> 00:21:22,980
 (speaking in foreign language)

317
00:21:22,980 --> 00:21:47,500
 So notice the satire here.

318
00:21:47,500 --> 00:21:50,020
 The author told us in verse 17 that Aglon,

319
00:21:50,020 --> 00:21:52,500
 he was a very fat man.

320
00:21:52,500 --> 00:21:54,020
 And this is not fat shaming,

321
00:21:54,020 --> 00:21:56,380
 but this is probably the results of him

322
00:21:56,380 --> 00:21:58,260
 getting fat and over the tribute

323
00:21:58,260 --> 00:22:00,580
 that he actually extorted from Israel

324
00:22:00,580 --> 00:22:03,100
 over the past 18 years.

325
00:22:03,100 --> 00:22:07,020
 (speaking in foreign language)

326
00:22:16,420 --> 00:22:17,860
 And then starting on verse 20,

327
00:22:17,860 --> 00:22:20,220
 everything went into slow motion.

328
00:22:20,220 --> 00:22:24,100
 See, Ehud then approached him

329
00:22:24,100 --> 00:22:27,700
 while he was sitting alone in the upper room of his palace

330
00:22:27,700 --> 00:22:32,220
 and said, "I have a message from God for you."

331
00:22:32,220 --> 00:22:34,420
 And as the king rose from his seat,

332
00:22:34,420 --> 00:22:36,700
 Ehud reached with his left hand,

333
00:22:36,700 --> 00:22:38,820
 drew the sword from his right thigh,

334
00:22:38,820 --> 00:22:41,700
 and plunged it into the king's belly.

335
00:22:41,700 --> 00:22:44,340
 Even the handle sank in after the blade

336
00:22:44,340 --> 00:22:46,020
 and his bowels discharged.

337
00:22:46,020 --> 00:22:48,580
 Ehud did not pull out the sword

338
00:22:48,580 --> 00:22:51,300
 and the fat closed in over it.

339
00:22:51,300 --> 00:22:53,060
 Then Ehud went out to the porch,

340
00:22:53,060 --> 00:22:55,620
 he shut the doors of the upper room behind him

341
00:22:55,620 --> 00:22:56,860
 and locked them.

342
00:22:56,860 --> 00:23:01,700
 (speaking in foreign language)

343
00:23:02,540 --> 00:23:06,460
 (speaking in foreign language)

344
00:23:07,460 --> 00:23:11,380
 (speaking in foreign language)

345
00:23:35,740 --> 00:23:39,540
 So here we actually see another trickery being revealed.

346
00:23:39,540 --> 00:23:42,300
 Ehud, he is not just delivering a tribute

347
00:23:42,300 --> 00:23:44,620
 from the oppressed Israel,

348
00:23:44,620 --> 00:23:46,860
 but he is God's means of deliverance

349
00:23:46,860 --> 00:23:48,740
 for the people of Israel.

350
00:23:48,740 --> 00:23:53,660
 Ehud, he is not just a messenger with a secret message,

351
00:23:53,660 --> 00:23:57,540
 but he is a messenger of God's judgment over Aglam.

352
00:23:57,540 --> 00:24:03,100
 (speaking in foreign language)

353
00:24:04,100 --> 00:24:08,020
 (speaking in foreign language)

354
00:24:08,020 --> 00:24:19,900
 And so even though Aglam had died at this point,

355
00:24:19,900 --> 00:24:22,820
 Israel's deliverance is not complete yet.

356
00:24:22,820 --> 00:24:23,660
 In the next few words,

357
00:24:23,660 --> 00:24:27,220
 we see more trickery and satire being played out.

358
00:24:27,220 --> 00:24:31,140
 (speaking in foreign language)

359
00:24:32,140 --> 00:24:36,060
 (speaking in foreign language)

360
00:24:36,060 --> 00:24:38,220
 We see here because Ehud,

361
00:24:38,220 --> 00:24:40,780
 he locked the door before he left the room.

362
00:24:40,780 --> 00:24:42,860
 So when the king's servant came,

363
00:24:42,860 --> 00:24:45,740
 they thought that their king was just having his time

364
00:24:45,740 --> 00:24:47,140
 using the bathroom.

365
00:24:47,140 --> 00:24:49,860
 So instead of going in and checking on their king,

366
00:24:49,860 --> 00:24:51,860
 they just waited outside.

367
00:24:51,860 --> 00:24:54,340
 And the smell of Aglam's bowel discharge

368
00:24:54,340 --> 00:24:57,500
 probably contributed to this as well.

369
00:24:57,500 --> 00:25:00,140
 (speaking in foreign language)

370
00:25:00,140 --> 00:25:04,060
 (speaking in foreign language)

371
00:25:04,060 --> 00:25:17,820
 So while the servants waited and waited outside,

372
00:25:17,820 --> 00:25:20,060
 this gave Ehud time to actually escape

373
00:25:20,060 --> 00:25:22,220
 and get back to his own people

374
00:25:22,220 --> 00:25:24,780
 to rally them for the final blow.

375
00:25:24,780 --> 00:25:28,700
 (speaking in foreign language)

376
00:25:28,700 --> 00:25:32,460
 (speaking in foreign language)

377
00:25:32,460 --> 00:25:35,140
 So let's pick up our story again from verse 28.

378
00:25:35,140 --> 00:25:37,740
 Follow me, Ehud ordered,

379
00:25:37,740 --> 00:25:41,860
 for the Lord has given Moab, your enemy, into your hands.

380
00:25:41,860 --> 00:25:43,140
 So they followed him down

381
00:25:43,140 --> 00:25:45,780
 and took possessions of the forts of the Jordan

382
00:25:45,780 --> 00:25:47,420
 that led to Moab,

383
00:25:47,420 --> 00:25:50,340
 and they allowed no one to cross over.

384
00:25:50,340 --> 00:25:53,660
 At that time, they struck down about 10,000 Moabites,

385
00:25:53,660 --> 00:25:57,060
 all vigorous and strong, not one escaped.

386
00:25:57,940 --> 00:26:00,900
 That day, Moab was made subject to Israel,

387
00:26:00,900 --> 00:26:04,100
 and the land had peace for 80 years.

388
00:26:04,100 --> 00:26:08,020
 (speaking in foreign language)

389
00:26:08,020 --> 00:26:11,940
 (speaking in foreign language)

390
00:26:11,940 --> 00:26:35,340
 And so here we see a total reversal of the roles

391
00:26:35,340 --> 00:26:37,700
 and a complete deliverance of Israel

392
00:26:37,700 --> 00:26:40,260
 from the hands of their oppressors.

393
00:26:40,260 --> 00:26:44,180
 (speaking in foreign language)

394
00:26:44,180 --> 00:26:49,180
 So while in verse 13, we saw that Eglon attacked Israel

395
00:26:49,180 --> 00:26:51,980
 and took possessions of the city of Palms,

396
00:26:51,980 --> 00:26:54,140
 here in verse 28 and 29,

397
00:26:54,140 --> 00:26:56,220
 Ehud and his men actually struck down

398
00:26:56,220 --> 00:26:58,700
 about 10,000 Moabite warriors,

399
00:26:58,700 --> 00:27:01,580
 and they took possessions of the forts of Jordan

400
00:27:01,580 --> 00:27:03,620
 that led to Moab.

401
00:27:03,620 --> 00:27:07,540
 (speaking in foreign language)

402
00:27:08,540 --> 00:27:12,460
 (speaking in foreign language)

403
00:27:12,460 --> 00:27:19,580
 And while in verse 14, the Israelites,

404
00:27:19,580 --> 00:27:24,300
 they were subject to Eglon, king of Moab, for 18 years,

405
00:27:24,300 --> 00:27:28,100
 here in verse 30, we saw that Moab actually became subject

406
00:27:28,100 --> 00:27:29,780
 to Israel that day,

407
00:27:29,780 --> 00:27:33,020
 and the Israelites and the land finally had peace

408
00:27:33,020 --> 00:27:34,580
 for 80 years.

409
00:27:34,620 --> 00:27:38,540
 (speaking in foreign language)

410
00:27:38,540 --> 00:27:48,140
 And so once again, this show us that God's holiness

411
00:27:48,140 --> 00:27:52,380
 and his love always work side by side in his rescues.

412
00:27:52,380 --> 00:27:55,340
 On one hand, God is holy and he is righteous.

413
00:27:55,340 --> 00:27:57,500
 So when his people sin against him,

414
00:27:57,500 --> 00:28:00,180
 he cannot let sin go unpunished.

415
00:28:00,180 --> 00:28:04,300
 But on the other hand, God is also love.

416
00:28:04,300 --> 00:28:06,620
 He understands that our human condition

417
00:28:06,620 --> 00:28:09,180
 and our need for a deliverer,

418
00:28:09,180 --> 00:28:13,060
 to deliver us not just from the enemies that is around us,

419
00:28:13,060 --> 00:28:16,980
 but more importantly, from the enemy that is within us,

420
00:28:16,980 --> 00:28:20,340
 that is our sinful and rebellious nature.

421
00:28:20,340 --> 00:28:24,260
 (speaking in foreign language)

422
00:28:24,260 --> 00:28:26,740
 And God's holy love is like a thread

423
00:28:26,740 --> 00:28:30,500
 that weaves through the entire story of the Bible.

424
00:28:30,500 --> 00:28:34,420
 (speaking in foreign language)

425
00:28:34,420 --> 00:28:39,100
 And God's love is like a thread

426
00:28:39,100 --> 00:28:43,020
 that weaves through the entire story of the Bible.

427
00:28:43,020 --> 00:28:46,940
 (speaking in foreign language)

428
00:28:46,940 --> 00:28:51,460
 And God's love is like a thread

429
00:28:51,460 --> 00:28:55,220
 that weaves through the entire story of the Bible.

430
00:28:55,220 --> 00:28:57,700
 We see his holy love in the way that he dealt with

431
00:28:57,700 --> 00:29:01,500
 the very first human couples, Adam and Eve.

432
00:29:01,500 --> 00:29:03,020
 Because Adam and Eve sin,

433
00:29:03,020 --> 00:29:05,980
 they have to be casted out from the garden of Eden

434
00:29:05,980 --> 00:29:10,740
 because sin can have no presence in the midst of God,

435
00:29:10,740 --> 00:29:12,580
 in the midst of a holy God.

436
00:29:12,580 --> 00:29:15,220
 But it is also out of love that they were banished

437
00:29:15,220 --> 00:29:16,700
 because they would literally die

438
00:29:16,700 --> 00:29:19,020
 if they continue to stay in Eden.

439
00:29:19,020 --> 00:29:22,940
 (speaking in foreign language)

440
00:29:22,940 --> 00:29:43,260
 And this theme of God's holy love

441
00:29:43,260 --> 00:29:46,340
 carries through from Genesis to Exodus,

442
00:29:46,340 --> 00:29:47,780
 into the promised land,

443
00:29:47,780 --> 00:29:51,100
 and eventually to Israel's exiles and the return.

444
00:29:51,100 --> 00:29:55,500
 And finally, God's holy love reaches climax

445
00:29:55,500 --> 00:29:58,300
 in the person of Jesus at the cross.

446
00:29:58,300 --> 00:30:01,220
 At the cross, we see that the wrath of God

447
00:30:01,220 --> 00:30:04,660
 was being poured out on the sins of the world.

448
00:30:04,660 --> 00:30:07,180
 And yet it wasn't us who had to bear

449
00:30:07,180 --> 00:30:09,460
 the consequences of our own sins,

450
00:30:09,460 --> 00:30:12,540
 but it was Jesus, the son of God himself,

451
00:30:12,540 --> 00:30:14,580
 taking on the sins of the world,

452
00:30:14,620 --> 00:30:16,220
 satisfying the wrath of the Father

453
00:30:16,220 --> 00:30:18,620
 because of His love for us.

454
00:30:18,620 --> 00:30:22,540
 (speaking in foreign language)

455
00:30:22,540 --> 00:30:48,940
 And so as we enter into a new year,

456
00:30:48,940 --> 00:30:51,820
 wherever you are in your journey with God,

457
00:30:51,820 --> 00:30:54,740
 I want to encourage all of us to take our next steps,

458
00:30:54,740 --> 00:30:57,580
 to grow in having a right understanding of God

459
00:30:57,580 --> 00:31:00,300
 as the embodiment of holy love

460
00:31:00,300 --> 00:31:02,860
 so that we can have deeper trust in Him.

461
00:31:02,860 --> 00:31:08,180
 (speaking in foreign language)

462
00:31:21,300 --> 00:31:22,220
 So let's pray.

463
00:31:22,220 --> 00:31:28,060
 Lord, we carry with us all kinds of false images

464
00:31:28,060 --> 00:31:30,700
 and wrong ideas when it comes to you all the time.

465
00:31:30,700 --> 00:31:36,060
 (speaking in foreign language)

466
00:31:36,060 --> 00:31:42,300
 And as we enter into a new year,

467
00:31:42,300 --> 00:31:44,580
 would you remind us again with the truth

468
00:31:44,580 --> 00:31:47,980
 that you are a holy and loving God?

469
00:31:47,980 --> 00:31:50,860
 You did not spare your own son,

470
00:31:50,860 --> 00:31:53,060
 but gave your only son, Jesus,

471
00:31:53,060 --> 00:31:56,140
 in order to deliver us from our sinfulness

472
00:31:56,140 --> 00:31:58,220
 and to give us eternal life.

473
00:31:58,220 --> 00:32:03,100
 (speaking in foreign language)

474
00:32:03,100 --> 00:32:18,620
 Help us to not take this gift for granted

475
00:32:19,780 --> 00:32:22,260
 and teach us to live a life of repentance

476
00:32:22,260 --> 00:32:26,700
 and a life of trust through the power of your Holy Spirit.

477
00:32:26,700 --> 00:32:30,620
 (speaking in foreign language)

478
00:32:30,620 --> 00:32:38,100
 And in your holy name we pray, amen.

479
00:32:38,100 --> 00:32:42,020
 (speaking in foreign language)

480
00:32:42,020 --> 00:32:45,460
 All right, brothers and sisters,

